Someone came to fix my kitchen floor, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can just open this cursed file. (Damn OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm in.
And that's when he starts drilling really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of turning my air purifier up full blast makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like sawdust, so it's justified even if he's an anti-masker. Plus, I really need to protect myself, right??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The good thing is, I've finished rereading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but it's full of suspense. Good work.
Doing some find-and-replace on … ➡️ ellipsis character, and there are 54 of them in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I insist. The most natural speeches are usually fragmented, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The craftsman is vacuuming, and with a bit of luck, he'll soon be done.
He went out (as far as I can hear) to cut something. So I took a look to see how he was doing. It's far from finished :(
Only 7 pages left on chapter five. It remains my favorite chapter, and it's quite complete. Some layout changes, and minor adjustments to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I would really like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still fiddling around in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The craftsman is gone!
He told me he had made a quote for the entire floor, but the owners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's definitely better.
The house is ventilated, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
